# IMP-0500

# Provider SDK Specification

Status: Draft

Version: 0.1

Depends on:

* RFC-0022 Provider Interface Specification
* IMP-0200 Hypervisor Service Interfaces
* IMP-0400 Package Organization and Coding Standards

---

# 1. Purpose

This document defines the official Provider SDK.

The SDK enables third-party developers to implement execution providers compatible with the AiDN Hypervisor.

The SDK SHALL abstract provider-specific implementation details behind a stable interface.

---

# 2. Design Goals

The Provider SDK SHALL:

* be implementation-independent;
* minimize boilerplate;
* support local and remote execution backends;
* expose deterministic lifecycle hooks;
* remain backward compatible across minor releases.

The SDK SHALL NOT expose Hypervisor internals.

---

# 3. Provider Responsibilities

A Provider is responsible only for execution.

A Provider SHALL NOT:

* participate in scheduling;
* publish Advertisements;
* access Wallet state;
* modify Endpoint metadata;
* communicate with the Registry;
* implement validation logic.

---

# 4. Provider Lifecycle

Every Provider SHALL implement:

```go id="zkt9m1"
type Provider interface {

    Initialize(ctx context.Context) error

    Start(ctx context.Context) error

    Stop(ctx context.Context) error

    Health(ctx context.Context) (HealthResult, error)

    Capabilities(ctx context.Context) (CapabilitiesResult, error)

    Bundles(ctx context.Context) (BundlesResult, error)

    LoadBundle(ctx context.Context, cmd LoadBundleCommand) (LoadBundleResult, error)

    UnloadBundle(ctx context.Context, cmd UnloadBundleCommand) (UnloadBundleResult, error)

    Execute(ctx context.Context, cmd ExecuteCommand) (ExecuteResult, error)

    Usage(ctx context.Context, cmd UsageCommand) (UsageResult, error)

    Warmup(ctx context.Context, cmd WarmupCommand) (WarmupResult, error)

    Shutdown(ctx context.Context) error
}
```

Every method SHALL be synchronous.

Long-running operations SHALL respect context cancellation.

---

# 5. Command and Result Objects

Every SDK operation SHALL use explicit Command and Result types.

Example:

```go id="jlwmn1"
type ExecuteCommand struct {
    EndpointID string
    RequestID  string
    Input      any
    Parameters map[string]any
}
```

```go id="jlwmn2"
type ExecuteResult struct {
    Output          any
    Usage           UsageReport
    ExecutionTimeMS int64
    Metadata        map[string]string
}
```

Primitive argument lists are prohibited.

---

# 6. Usage Reporting

Providers SHALL report usage using Billing Units.

Example:

```go id="jlwmn3"
type UsageReport struct {

    BillingUnit string

    InputUnits float64

    OutputUnits float64

    MeasurementKind string

    MeasurementSource string
}
```

Examples of Billing Units include:

* token
* second
* image
* page
* request

Custom Billing Units MAY be introduced by future Capabilities.

---

# 7. Health Reporting

Health SHALL include:

```go id="jlwmn4"
type HealthResult struct {

    Status

    ActiveRequests

    LoadedBundles

    LastError

    Uptime
}
```

Health SHALL describe observable runtime state only.

---

# 8. Bundle Support

Providers SHALL expose the Bundles they currently support.

Bundle loading SHALL be idempotent.

Attempting to load an already loaded Bundle SHALL succeed without side effects.

---

# 9. Error Model

SDK errors SHALL use structured error types.

Every error SHALL include:

* Code
* Message
* Recoverable
* Cause (optional)

Providers SHALL NOT panic for recoverable execution failures.

---

# 10. Thread Safety

Providers SHALL support concurrent Execute operations unless explicitly documented otherwise.

Thread safety guarantees SHALL be published through Provider metadata.

---

# 11. Configuration

Providers SHALL receive immutable configuration during initialization.

Runtime configuration changes SHALL occur only through Hypervisor-managed Configuration Snapshots.

Providers SHALL NOT reload configuration autonomously.

---

# 12. Resource Reporting

Providers MAY publish resource hints.

Example:

```go id="jlwmn5"
type ResourceEstimate struct {

    EstimatedRAM

    EstimatedVRAM

    EstimatedCPU

    EstimatedGPU
}
```

The Hypervisor MAY use these hints during scheduling.

Resource hints are advisory.

---

# 13. Logging

Providers SHALL use the logging interface supplied by the Hypervisor.

Providers SHALL NOT create independent logging systems.

---

# 14. Metrics

Providers MAY emit execution metrics.

Metrics SHALL be observational only.

Providers SHALL NOT modify Hypervisor metrics directly.

---

# 15. Testing Requirements

Every Provider implementation SHALL include:

* lifecycle tests;
* execution tests;
* cancellation tests;
* concurrent execution tests;
* usage reporting tests;
* health reporting tests.

Reference test suites SHALL be supplied by the Hypervisor project.

---

# 16. Compatibility

Providers SHALL declare:

* SDK Version
* Provider Version
* Supported Capabilities
* Supported Model Classes
* Supported Bundle Formats

The Hypervisor SHALL reject incompatible SDK versions.

---

# 17. Extension Rules

New SDK methods SHALL be added only through interface versioning.

Existing methods SHALL remain backward compatible throughout the major SDK version.

---

# 18. Design Invariants

Invariant 1

Providers execute workloads.

Nothing more.

---

Invariant 2

Providers never participate in network protocols.

---

Invariant 3

Billing is reported, never calculated.

---

Invariant 4

The Hypervisor owns orchestration.

Providers own execution.

---

Invariant 5

The SDK remains transport-independent.

Local processes, remote APIs and future execution engines SHALL implement the same contract.
